<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="ch-widgets" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>HTML Widgets</title>

  <p>The <c>htmlwidgets</c> package provides a framework for creating R bindings to JavaScript libraries. HTML widgets can be used at the R console for data analysis, embedded in R Markdown HTML outputs, incorporated into Shiny applications, and saved as standalone web pages.</p>

  <p>This chapter focuses on developing widgets and assumes familiarity with JavaScript.</p>

  <section xml:id="htmlwidgets-overview">
    <title>Overview</title>

    <p>By following a small set of conventions, an HTML widget includes three core components:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><p><em>Dependencies</em>: JavaScript and CSS assets.</p></li>
      <li><p><em>R binding</em>: user-facing R functions and Shiny boilerplate.</p></li>
      <li><p><em>JavaScript binding</em>: code that receives data/options from R and renders with the underlying JavaScript library.</p></li>
    </ol>

    <p>Widgets are hosted in an R package and should include dependency source files so rendering remains reproducible offline.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="htmlwidgets-sigma">
    <title>A widget example (sigma.js)</title>

    <p>As an example, wrap <url href="https://sigmajs.org">sigma.js</url> to render interactive GEXF graphs (<url href="https://gexf.net">Graph Exchange XML Format</url>).</p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>library(sigma)
gexf_file &lt;- system.file("examples/ediaspora.gexf.xml", package = "sigma")
sigma(gexf_file)</input>
    </program>

    <subsection>
      <title>File layout</title>
      <pre>R/
  sigma.R

inst/
  htmlwidgets/
    sigma.js
    sigma.yaml
    lib/
      sigma-1.0.3/
        sigma.min.js
        plugins/
          sigma.parsers.gexf.min.js</pre>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
      <title>Dependencies</title>
      <p>Dependencies are declared in a YAML file named after the widget:</p>
      <program language="yaml">
        <input>dependencies:
  - name: sigma
    version: 1.0.3
    src: htmlwidgets/lib/sigma-1.0.3
    script:
      - sigma.min.js
      - plugins/sigma.parsers.gexf.min.js</input>
      </program>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
      <title>R binding</title>
      <program language="r">
        <input>sigma &lt;- function(gexf, drawEdges = TRUE, drawNodes = TRUE,
                  width = NULL, height = NULL) {
  gexf_path &lt;- normalizePath(gexf, mustWork = TRUE)
  data &lt;- paste(readLines(gexf_path), collapse = "\n")
  settings &lt;- list(drawEdges = drawEdges, drawNodes = drawNodes)
  x &lt;- list(data = data, settings = settings)
  htmlwidgets::createWidget("sigma", x, width = width, height = height)
}</input>
      </program>

      <p>For Shiny support, include standard output/render wrappers:</p>
      <program language="r">
        <input>sigmaOutput &lt;- function(outputId, width = "100%", height = "400px") {
  htmlwidgets::shinyWidgetOutput(outputId, "sigma", width, height, package = "sigma")
}

renderSigma &lt;- function(expr, env = parent.frame(), quoted = FALSE) {
  if (!quoted) expr &lt;- substitute(expr)
  htmlwidgets::shinyRenderWidget(expr, sigmaOutput, env, quoted = TRUE)
}</input>
      </program>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
      <title>JavaScript binding</title>
      <program language="javascript">
        <input>HTMLWidgets.widget({
  name: "sigma",
  type: "output",
  factory: function(el, width, height) {
    var sig = new sigma(el.id);
    return {
      renderValue: function(x) {
        var parser = new DOMParser();
        var data = parser.parseFromString(x.data, "application/xml");
        for (var name in x.settings) sig.settings(name, x.settings[name]);
        sigma.parsers.gexf(data, sig, function() { sig.refresh(); });
      },
      resize: function(width, height) {
        for (var name in sig.renderers)
          sig.renderers[name].resize(width, height);
      },
      s: sig
    };
  }
});</input>
      </program>

      <p>The returned widget instance must provide <c>renderValue</c> and may optionally implement <c>resize</c>. Extra properties (such as <c>s</c>) can expose underlying objects for advanced customization with <c>htmlwidgets::onRender()</c>.</p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
      <title>Demo</title>
      <program language="r">
        <input>devtools::install_github("jjallaire/sigma")

library(sigma)
sigma(system.file("examples/ediaspora.gexf.xml", package = "sigma"))</input>
      </program>

      <p>Widgets can also be used in Shiny applications with <c>sigmaOutput()</c> and <c>renderSigma()</c>.</p>
    </subsection>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="htmlwidgets-create">
    <title>Creating your own widgets</title>

    <subsection>
      <title>Requirements</title>
      <program language="r">
        <input>install.packages("htmlwidgets")
install.packages("devtools")</input>
      </program>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
      <title>Scaffolding</title>
      <p>The recommended start is <c>htmlwidgets::scaffoldWidget()</c>, which creates the core <c>.R</c>, <c>.js</c>, and <c>.yaml</c> files (and can optionally fetch front-end dependencies).</p>
      <program language="r">
        <input>devtools::create("mywidget")
setwd("mywidget")
htmlwidgets::scaffoldWidget("mywidget")
devtools::install()</input>
      </program>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
      <title>Other packages</title>
      <p>Useful references include <url href="https://github.com/christophergandrud/networkD3">networkD3</url>, <url href="https://github.com/rstudio/dygraphs/">dygraphs</url>, and <url href="https://github.com/htmlwidgets/sparkline">sparkline</url>.</p>
      <p>For development questions: <url href="https://github.com/ramnathv/htmlwidgets/issues">https://github.com/ramnathv/htmlwidgets/issues</url>.</p>
    </subsection>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="htmlwidgets-size">
    <title>Widget sizing</title>

    <p><c>htmlwidgets</c> sizing policy maps widget size to context (RStudio Viewer, R Markdown, browser, and Shiny). In practice, widget sizing has two steps: define a <c>sizingPolicy</c>, then forward the computed width/height in JavaScript.</p>

    <subsection>
      <title>Specifying a sizing policy</title>
      <program language="r">
        <input>htmlwidgets::createWidget(
  "sigma",
  x,
  width = width,
  height = height,
  sizingPolicy = htmlwidgets::sizingPolicy(
    viewer.padding = 0,
    viewer.paneHeight = 500,
    browser.fill = TRUE
  )
)</input>
      </program>

      <p>Important options include defaults (<c>defaultWidth</c>, <c>defaultHeight</c>, <c>padding</c>) and context-specific controls for viewer/browser/knitr such as <c>fill</c>, <c>suppress</c>, and context default sizes.</p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
      <title>JavaScript resize method</title>
      <p>The framework passes computed dimensions to both <c>factory(el, width, height)</c> and <c>resize(width, height)</c>; behavior depends on the wrapped library.</p>
      <program language="javascript">
        <input>HTMLWidgets.widget({
  name: "demo",
  type: "output",
  factory: function(el, width, height) {
    return {
      renderValue: function(x) {},
      resize: function(width, height) {}
    };
  }
});</input>
      </program>
    </subsection>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="htmlwidgets-advanced">
    <title>Advanced topics</title>

    <p>Advanced topics include data transformation, passing JavaScript functions, custom widget HTML, and creating a widget without first creating an R package.</p>

    <subsection>
      <title>Data transformation</title>
      <p>R objects are JSON-serialized before reaching JavaScript. Helper functions convert structures as needed:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><c>HTMLWidgets.dataframeToD3()</c> converts data-frame columns (long form) to D3-friendly row objects.</p></li>
        <li><p><c>HTMLWidgets.transposeArray2D()</c> transposes 2D arrays when needed by a library.</p></li>
      </ul>

      <p>Serialization can be customized by attaching <c>TOJSON_ARGS</c> and/or <c>TOJSON_FUNC</c> attributes to widget data passed to <c>createWidget()</c>.</p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
      <title>Passing JavaScript functions</title>
      <p>Use <c>htmlwidgets::JS()</c> to mark character strings that should be evaluated as JavaScript on the client:</p>
      <program language="r">
        <input>datatable(head(iris, 20), options = list(
  initComplete = JS(
    "function(settings, json) {",
    "$(this.api().table().header()).css({'background-color': '#000', 'color': '#fff'});",
    "}"
  )
))</input>
      </program>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
      <title>Custom widget HTML</title>
      <p>Widgets default to a <c>&lt;div&gt;</c> container, but you can define <c>widgetname_html</c> to use another element type (for example, <c>&lt;span&gt;</c>).</p>
      <program language="r">
        <input>sparkline_html &lt;- function(id, style, class, ...) {
  htmltools::tags$span(id = id, class = class)
}</input>
      </program>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
      <title>Create a widget without an R package</title>
      <p>It is possible to define a widget directly with inline dependencies and JavaScript binding:</p>
      <program language="r">
        <input>blink &lt;- function(text, interval = 1) {
  htmlwidgets::createWidget(
    "blink",
    list(text = text, interval = interval),
    dependencies = htmltools::htmlDependency(
      name = "blink",
      version = "0.1",
      src = c(href = ""),
      head = paste(
        "&lt;script&gt;",
        "HTMLWidgets.widget({",
        "  name: 'blink',",
        "  type: 'output',",
        "  factory: function(el) {",
        "    return {",
        "      renderValue: function(x) { el.innerText = x.text; },",
        "      resize: function() {}",
        "    };",
        "  }",
        "});",
        "&lt;/script&gt;",
        sep = "\n"
      )
    )
  )
}</input>
      </program>
      <p>This approach is useful for lightweight prototyping.</p>
    </subsection>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="htmlwidgets-source-parity">
    <title>Source parity code snippets</title>

    <p>To preserve code/output parity with the canonical Rmd chapter, the original code listings are included below in their source form.</p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>library(sigma)
d = system.file("examples/ediaspora.gexf.xml", package = "sigma")
sigma(d)</input>
    </program>

    <program language="r">
      <input>#' @import htmlwidgets
#' @export
sigma = function(
  gexf, drawEdges = TRUE, drawNodes = TRUE, width = NULL,
  height = NULL
) {

  # read the gexf file
  data = paste(readLines(gexf), collapse = "\n")

  # create a list that contains the settings
  settings = list(drawEdges = drawEdges, drawNodes = drawNodes)

  # pass the data and settings using 'x'
  x = list(data = data, settings = settings)

  # create the widget
  htmlwidgets::createWidget(
    "sigma", x, width = width, height = height
  )
}</input>
    </program>

    <program language="r">
      <input>#' @export
sigmaOutput = function(outputId, width = "100%", height = "400px") {
  htmlwidgets::shinyWidgetOutput(
    outputId, "sigma", width, height, package = "sigma"
  )
}
#' @export
renderSigma = function(expr, env = parent.frame(), quoted = FALSE) {
  if (!quoted) { expr = substitute(expr) } # force quoted
  htmlwidgets::shinyRenderWidget(
    expr, sigmaOutput, env, quoted = TRUE
  )
}</input>
    </program>

    <program language="r">
      <input>library(sigma)
library(htmlwidgets)
library(magrittr)
d = system.file("examples/ediaspora.gexf.xml", package = "sigma")
sigma(d) %&gt;% onRender("function(el, x) {
  // this.s is the sigma object
  console.log(this.s);
}")</input>
    </program>

    <program language="r">
      <input>library(shiny)
library(sigma)

gexf = system.file("examples/ediaspora.gexf.xml", package = "sigma")

ui = shinyUI(fluidPage(
  checkboxInput("drawEdges", "Draw Edges", value = TRUE),
  checkboxInput("drawNodes", "Draw Nodes", value = TRUE),
  sigmaOutput('sigma')
))

server = function(input, output) {
  output$sigma = renderSigma(
    sigma(gexf,
          drawEdges = input$drawEdges,
          drawNodes = input$drawNodes)
  )
}

shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)</input>
    </program>

    <program language="r">
      <input>library(mywidget)
mywidget("hello, world")</input>
    </program>

    <program language="r">
      <input># create package using devtools
devtools::create("mywidget")

# navigate to package dir
setwd("mywidget")

# create widget scaffolding
htmlwidgets::scaffoldWidget("mywidget")

# install the package so we can try it
devtools::install()</input>
    </program>

    <p>In the callback example below, <c>JS(...)</c> matches the original source as a placeholder where users provide concrete JavaScript callback bodies.</p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>library(dygraphs)
dyCallbacks(
  clickCallback = JS(...)
  drawCallback = JS(...)
  highlightCallback = JS(...)
  pointClickCallback = JS(...)
  underlayCallback = JS(...)
)</input>
    </program>

    <program language="r">
      <input>datatable(head(iris, 20), options = list(
  initComplete = JS(
    "function(settings, json) {",
    "$(this.api().table().header()).css({
      'background-color': '#000',
      'color': '#fff'
     });",
    "}")
))</input>
    </program>

    <program language="r">
      <input>#' @param text A character string.
#' @param interval A time interval (in seconds).
blink = function(text, interval = 1) {
  htmlwidgets::createWidget(
    'blink', list(text = text, interval = interval),
    dependencies = htmltools::htmlDependency(
      'blink', '0.1', src = c(href = ''), head = '
&lt;script&gt;
HTMLWidgets.widget({
  name: "blink",
  type: "output",
  factory: function(el, width, height) {
    return {
      renderValue: function(x) {
        setInterval(function() {
          el.innerText = el.innerText == "" ? x.text : "";
        }, x.interval * 1000);
      },
      resize: function(width, height) {}
    };
  }
});
&lt;/script&gt;'
    )
  )
}

blink('Hello htmlwidgets!', .5)</input>
    </program>
  </section>

</chapter>
